1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:04,416
The talk is about the quest according to the Buddha.

2
00:00:05,658 --> 00:00:10,022
I suppose the best thing is to relate to you the story of the Buddha himself.

3
00:00:10,124 --> 00:00:23,239
I'm sure you know the bare bones of it, but in a sense, his story is the archetype, really, of anybody who's on the spiritual path.

4
00:00:23,260 --> 00:00:24,080
So...

5
00:00:27,772 --> 00:00:33,798
There are lots of legends around, you know, what happened to him before, you know, the way he lived and whatnot.

6
00:00:33,819 --> 00:00:39,243
But basically he was the son of a local lord, a local chieftain.

7
00:00:39,264 --> 00:00:42,267
Yeah, that's the chieftain.

8
00:00:42,286 --> 00:00:44,689
And a kshatriya.

9
00:00:44,710 --> 00:00:47,972
So he would have been brought up in the art of war and government.

10
00:00:48,432 --> 00:00:50,174
And that was the duty of his caste.

11
00:00:52,156 --> 00:00:53,037
And...

12
00:00:55,246 --> 00:01:00,700
It was a time of great change, moving from pastoral society to

13
00:01:02,131 --> 00:01:04,894
the first monarchical systems.

14
00:01:05,756 --> 00:01:10,161
So already the Sakyas were subject to the king of Kosala.

15
00:01:10,180 --> 00:01:21,194
So they weren't, as they were, say, a bit before the Buddha's time, tribes who had their own democratic way of governing themselves.

16
00:01:21,555 --> 00:01:28,944
Democratic in the sense that the Greeks thought of democracy, you know, just the ruling caste sharing the power.

17
00:01:31,007 --> 00:01:31,108
Yeah.

18
00:01:31,087 --> 00:01:53,197
So within that change there was not only the growth of kingship and local power, three or four kings around the Buddha, but the cities grew and trade grew and a new caste you might say arose within an already existing caste, the merchants became very rich.

19
00:01:54,427 --> 00:01:57,638
So that sort of shifted the balance of power a bit.

20
00:01:58,621 --> 00:02:02,918
And at the time of the Buddha the castes weren't so solid.

21
00:02:03,082 --> 00:02:03,983
as they became.

22
00:02:04,965 --> 00:02:11,413
So the idea that the Brahmins were the head of society had not yet been fully established.

23
00:02:11,432 --> 00:02:16,479
It seems as though it had been established towards what we call Bengal, Calcutta way.

24
00:02:17,080 --> 00:02:19,643
But where he was in the middle, it was still fairly fluid.

25
00:02:20,264 --> 00:02:24,008
So when you read the scriptures, it's always the Buddha telling them what a real Brahmin is.

26
00:02:25,871 --> 00:02:27,893
And suggesting that they weren't as great as they thought.

27
00:02:30,286 --> 00:02:40,039
So, you know, it's around about the age of 29, that's what he said, that he left the home life.

28
00:02:40,060 --> 00:02:47,891
And I'm sure you all experienced in your mid-twenties a growing realisation that, you know, nobody under 25, is there?

29
00:02:50,235 --> 00:02:54,140
That youth had actually, or was coming rather rapidly to an end.

30
00:02:54,822 --> 00:02:58,486
And that one had better get serious about life, and it's normally a time you might...

31
00:02:58,467 --> 00:03:01,211
If you're really forward-looking, take out a pension.

32
00:03:01,951 --> 00:03:08,661
Start to take your work seriously and even start a relationship with true intent.

33
00:03:09,322 --> 00:03:14,368
So it's a shift within our consciousness around about the age of, you know, the mid-twenties.

34
00:03:14,389 --> 00:03:17,413
And for some, it's an early existential crisis, you know.

35
00:03:18,433 --> 00:03:24,862
And I suppose you could reduce the spiritual path to maybe three questions.

36
00:03:26,530 --> 00:03:29,697
The first one being something like, who am I, or what am I?

37
00:03:31,520 --> 00:03:33,825
The second one being, you know, how do I relate?

38
00:03:34,227 --> 00:03:35,068
How do I fit in?

39
00:03:36,551 --> 00:03:38,436
And the third one being, you know, what do I do?

40
00:03:38,496 --> 00:03:46,193
And those are your three paths, the path of understanding or insight, the path of love, and the path of action, okay?

41
00:03:48,907 --> 00:04:13,158
so at that time because of the disturbance in society there was a growing what something like the hippie movement everybody a lot of people men leaving the home life to live as ascetics wanderers and they were well accepted by society they were considered to be worthy of support

42
00:04:14,016 --> 00:04:21,146
And what they were trying to do was to find the end of rebirth.

43
00:04:21,466 --> 00:04:28,394
The thing that obsessed the mind at that time was this idea of constantly being reborn, having to come back.

44
00:04:28,475 --> 00:04:43,432
And it's okay if times are good, but because those times weren't so good, and there's a lot of anxiety in the air, the question of how do you bring that whole process, the samsara, the onward-going process to an end?

45
00:04:43,649 --> 00:04:46,612
So various teachers at the Buddha's time had various answers.

46
00:04:46,653 --> 00:04:48,875
Some were what we would call materialists.

47
00:04:48,894 --> 00:04:51,577
You just, you live this life and you died and that was it.

48
00:04:53,180 --> 00:04:57,685
Some thought that the passage of karmic lives was completely said.

49
00:04:57,725 --> 00:04:59,827
It was fate.

50
00:05:01,170 --> 00:05:08,978
So they didn't mind whether you went down one side of the Ganges pillaging and murdering and all that and come up the other side with great acts of compassion.

51
00:05:09,019 --> 00:05:09,980
It made no difference at all.

52
00:05:10,581 --> 00:05:12,963
Whatever you were supposed to be born in the next life, that was going to happen.

53
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:16,161
And there were others.

54
00:05:16,322 --> 00:05:21,005
The Jain leader, of course, was an elder contemporary of the Buddha.

55
00:05:22,728 --> 00:05:35,761
And they had the idea, which I think was also within the Brahminical system, that there was stuff sort of clinging onto the soul, the jīva.

56
00:05:37,242 --> 00:05:40,285
And it was done by action, but it was like stuff clinging.

57
00:05:41,242 --> 00:05:44,608
And the way to bring it to an end was to really stop.

58
00:05:45,430 --> 00:05:45,992
Just stop.

59
00:05:46,673 --> 00:05:47,834
Stop creating karma.

60
00:05:48,035 --> 00:05:52,242
So you know the Jains are very wary of stepping on creatures and stuff like that.

61
00:05:52,524 --> 00:05:54,387
Because even if you don't mean it, it's bad news.

62
00:05:57,252 --> 00:06:01,560
And the Jain saint basically starves himself to death.

63
00:06:02,401 --> 00:06:05,326
You bring your karma to an end by just ending your life.

64
00:06:11,163 --> 00:06:25,644
So when the Buddha left the home life, he left not only because of perhaps joining the obsession of the age, of trying to work out, you know, was there an end to this rebirth thing?

65
00:06:25,663 --> 00:06:31,531
It was also because he'd sort of become disenchanted with what society had to offer.

66
00:06:34,136 --> 00:06:38,401
And one image that comes through the scriptures is that he's at a party.

67
00:06:39,495 --> 00:06:43,461
And at the end of the party, all he sees is disheveled bodies and people being drunk and whatnot.

68
00:06:44,182 --> 00:06:46,264
And it's like, well, what's all this about?

69
00:06:46,985 --> 00:06:52,874
It's sort of an emptiness of the sensual life, really.

70
00:06:55,076 --> 00:06:57,639
And that was part of his disillusionment.

71
00:06:58,461 --> 00:07:05,571
And all he could see ahead of him was this ordinary type of living, just trying to be happy all the time, with sensual pleasure.

72
00:07:07,204 --> 00:07:14,995
And the other part was a more existential insight, which is put in the myth that he was out riding in his chariot or whatever.

73
00:07:16,716 --> 00:07:22,624
And he came across a sick person, a very old person, and a corpse, and an ascetic sitting under a tree.

74
00:07:24,245 --> 00:07:27,891
And this just awoke in him the fact that, you know, this is the facts of life.

75
00:07:27,951 --> 00:07:31,896
This is, you know, you get sick, you grow old, and then you die, you know.

76
00:07:32,146 --> 00:07:34,192
The old comedian said, life's hard and then you die.

77
00:07:37,841 --> 00:07:46,206
But this idea of an aesthetic under a tree awoke in him some sort of hope, some sort of idea that maybe there was an end to this process.

78
00:07:49,696 --> 00:07:56,221
And so he goes off, leaving the ordinary household life, leaving really sensual pleasure.

79
00:07:56,362 --> 00:07:57,122
And that's what he's left.

80
00:07:57,223 --> 00:08:00,625
He doesn't see any future in sensual pleasure.

81
00:08:01,927 --> 00:08:04,168
And he's very sort of dramatic.

82
00:08:04,730 --> 00:08:16,160
He leaves his newly born child and he peeks through the curtain of the door and he doesn't look because it would draw him back into the household life and he leaves.

83
00:08:17,480 --> 00:08:19,483
So these days, of course, that sounds like abandonment.

84
00:08:22,247 --> 00:08:22,968
which it was.

85
00:08:24,209 --> 00:08:28,375
But a man's got to do what a man...

86
00:08:28,394 --> 00:08:47,918
I remember in those days there would have been the extended family if not as though she was destitute and also he talks about his mother and father were crying and with tearful eyes saying goodbye to him so it was all set up and he probably did what I did to my mother and said well I'm only going for three years

87
00:08:49,702 --> 00:08:50,403
Because that's what happened.

88
00:08:51,606 --> 00:08:53,350
I said, I'm going to become a monk for three years.

89
00:08:53,571 --> 00:08:55,794
I had never heard anybody cry like that before in my life.

90
00:08:56,336 --> 00:08:58,961
And I put my arm around her and said, it's only for three years.

91
00:08:59,042 --> 00:09:01,847
And she stopped.

92
00:09:01,868 --> 00:09:08,421
So I presume it was that sort of goodbye that there was a presumption that he'd have a go and then he'd come back.

93
00:09:09,817 --> 00:09:20,294
So the first thing he does is he goes off and he hears about these two very good teachers who both say they've achieved nirvana, they've achieved the end of suffering.

94
00:09:20,315 --> 00:09:24,280
And what they teach him became part of his system of teaching.

95
00:09:24,381 --> 00:09:27,746
We call it the jhanas or the absorption states.

96
00:09:27,767 --> 00:09:32,754
And the way that you attain these is through mantra practice, through watching the breath,

97
00:09:33,442 --> 00:09:50,115
Slowly but surely you build up a beautiful state within yourself and this state becomes quite calm, it can become ecstatic and you lose contact with the physical world, you lose contact with the body and it's like a little bubble inside you that you can live in.

98
00:09:50,975 --> 00:09:55,485
And depending on the strength of your concentration and practice you can stay there for quite some time.

99
00:09:57,322 --> 00:10:17,490
one of them taught him to go to a certain stage and the next one taught him to go one stage higher and both of them especially the second one saw him as an equal and both of them invited him to be a teacher co-teacher but his response was that there was something wrong he hadn't actually

100
00:10:17,470 --> 00:10:38,432
completed he hadn't actually answered his question because when you came out of these states he was still the same old depressed Siddhartha you know so he left that and he thought well the thing to try now is the other way which was self-mortification and that's where the Jain leader we think had an effect on his practice

101
00:10:41,466 --> 00:10:48,096
So this idea of desire is rooted in the Brahminical tradition that the problem is desire.

102
00:10:48,115 --> 00:10:50,119
Even Socrates was aware of that.

103
00:10:51,900 --> 00:10:55,905
And one understanding was that it was the body that was at fault.

104
00:10:55,926 --> 00:11:00,272
It was the body that gave us hunger and lust and avarice and all that.

105
00:11:00,351 --> 00:11:01,494
It was rooted in the body.

106
00:11:01,913 --> 00:11:10,004
So if you left society and really starved the body, really stopped feeding into it, then...

107
00:11:11,234 --> 00:11:14,999
That would bring you to the end of karma, that sort of idea.

108
00:11:16,220 --> 00:11:18,663
I'm sure you've all done a 10-day fast.

109
00:11:20,905 --> 00:11:21,005
Yeah?

110
00:11:21,025 --> 00:11:21,086
No?

111
00:11:21,105 --> 00:11:21,407
Okay.

112
00:11:22,347 --> 00:11:26,393
Well, if you have, you'll know that the first three days are horrible while the body releases toxins.

113
00:11:26,893 --> 00:11:29,897
But then after that, you feel very light, very wonderful.

114
00:11:30,037 --> 00:11:30,999
You don't want to eat at all.

115
00:11:32,100 --> 00:11:34,903
Of course, you're dying, but that's irrelevant.

116
00:11:34,984 --> 00:11:38,607
It's a very happy, calm state of mind.

117
00:11:39,178 --> 00:11:51,438
So it does have that sort of an effect and he goes through this business of eating so little that he says he could hold his spine through his stomach and stuff like that.

118
00:11:51,458 --> 00:11:55,485
And what he found was it was just painful.

119
00:11:57,489 --> 00:11:59,432
And that didn't seem to get him anywhere either.

120
00:12:00,003 --> 00:12:05,292
Self-mortification was just painful and unprofitable, ignoble, he actually says.

121
00:12:05,312 --> 00:12:10,139
So he left that, and by that time he had five companions.

122
00:12:10,660 --> 00:12:24,102
And as the myth goes, you know, the little story that surrounds it, he's left them and he's gone onto a roadside, and a woman, Sujata, comes along with a bit of rice pudding.

123
00:12:25,163 --> 00:12:30,610
So you all know the selfific effect of rice pudding, yeah?

124
00:12:30,671 --> 00:12:34,014
So this woman offers it, and it sort of revives him, you know?

125
00:12:34,836 --> 00:12:44,889
And for some reason, and maybe because it was rice pudding, he remembers this moment in childhood, and this is a sort of key moment in his life.

126
00:12:45,510 --> 00:12:47,913
He's watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

127
00:12:49,278 --> 00:12:58,471
And there's something about that watching which is different from these meditations that he's been doing with these people.

128
00:12:58,932 --> 00:13:04,240
So the meditation he's been doing with these two teachers had been about creating a state of mind.

129
00:13:05,361 --> 00:13:09,008
Like we do when, for instance, we're a bit bored and we turn the TV on.

130
00:13:09,105 --> 00:13:11,892
See, as soon as you turn the TV on, you get a different state of mind.

131
00:13:12,855 --> 00:13:15,701
And they'd been unsatisfactory.

132
00:13:16,121 --> 00:13:25,062
But there's something about this watching of his father which awoke in him the possibility.

133
00:13:25,823 --> 00:13:27,047
This was something different.

134
00:13:28,293 --> 00:13:31,677
And what it was, was that he was still very concentrated.

135
00:13:31,716 --> 00:13:42,370
He recognized that the state he was in as a child had that same level of concentration that he got through these meditative exercises.

136
00:13:44,094 --> 00:13:44,914
But he was watching.

137
00:13:45,495 --> 00:13:47,398
But he was...

138
00:13:49,048 --> 00:13:51,292
beginning to understand what his father was doing.

139
00:13:51,692 --> 00:14:01,342
So something else had come into the equation, which was then what he called the wisdom factor, the panna, this intuitive intelligence.

140
00:14:01,363 --> 00:14:07,690
So if your intent is just to make yourself happy, I mean, there's no problem in investigating anything.

141
00:14:08,331 --> 00:14:09,511
If it makes you happy, that's fine.

142
00:14:10,432 --> 00:14:11,073
Why worry?

143
00:14:12,201 --> 00:14:17,230
But if something doesn't make you happy, if something goes wrong, like with your washing machine or something, then you want to know.

144
00:14:17,270 --> 00:14:20,115
There's that wanting to know.

145
00:14:20,135 --> 00:14:25,684
So although he had this wanting to know, he wanted to know whether there was an end to suffering, there was still...

146
00:14:26,486 --> 00:14:31,394
The exercises being given were just creating beautiful states of mind, which also came to an end.

147
00:14:32,998 --> 00:14:33,619
Why...

148
00:14:33,802 --> 00:14:37,206
It didn't occur to him then to investigate those.

149
00:14:37,226 --> 00:14:41,594
It was probably because the people he was surrounded with were telling him, well, no, this is it.

150
00:14:41,634 --> 00:14:42,315
There is no more.

151
00:14:43,216 --> 00:14:51,028
There was no inkling as to how to move further with that sort of system.

152
00:14:51,729 --> 00:14:55,674
And, you know, the self-mortification, I mean, that was just painful.

153
00:14:56,211 --> 00:15:16,195
So this memory then, he decided to continue his practice, and he found a nice place near Uruvela, which is now Bodh Gaya, and a nice bit of, I think you call it tusagras, so you could sit comfortably, you see, so you always start comfortable, and he sat there, and

154
00:15:16,985 --> 00:15:20,769
He made this determination that now he couldn't see any other possibility.

155
00:15:20,788 --> 00:15:22,431
He said, now I'm going to sit here.

156
00:15:23,111 --> 00:15:26,034
Either I'm going to crack this problem or I'm going to die.

157
00:15:26,455 --> 00:15:28,356
So it was a very firm determination.

158
00:15:29,719 --> 00:15:34,524
Luckily, the bluff wasn't called because he did actually make insight.

159
00:15:35,325 --> 00:15:37,866
Now, the insights were three.

160
00:15:38,187 --> 00:15:45,995
He had three insights which gave him an understanding and also liberated him.

161
00:15:46,988 --> 00:16:13,873
because of his very good concentration he was able to direct his attention to past lives and if you want to do it I'll tell you where you can get the technique you have to have very strong concentration and as he went through his past lives what he saw was that in passing from one life to the next it depended upon the moral

162
00:16:14,022 --> 00:16:18,250
quality of the life before, on the ethical value of the life before.

163
00:16:18,971 --> 00:16:23,780
Now, this was not the way the Brahmins thought at the time.

164
00:16:24,140 --> 00:16:28,690
Karma for the Brahmins was to do the ritual properly.

165
00:16:29,142 --> 00:16:37,852
So remember, the early polytheistic societies, they personalized forces in nature.

166
00:16:38,033 --> 00:16:40,155
So, you know, the sun god, things like that.

167
00:16:41,037 --> 00:16:46,745
And the first sacrifices were there to propitiate these gods to get what you wanted.

168
00:16:47,164 --> 00:16:48,547
It was an asking, you see.

169
00:16:49,447 --> 00:16:57,158
Later on, it became more that if you did the ritual perfectly right, the god had to answer.

170
00:16:57,796 --> 00:17:01,802
So your karma was getting the ritual perfectly right.

171
00:17:01,942 --> 00:17:03,244
It had nothing to do with ethics.

172
00:17:04,226 --> 00:17:11,096
So the entrance of ethics into the Indian system was, according to the books I've read, was peculiar to the Buddha.

173
00:17:11,356 --> 00:17:13,881
It came later on, of course, in Hinduism.

174
00:17:15,615 --> 00:17:24,828
So he saw that this was true of his own life, that depending on his model actions, good or bad in the past life, he would be reborn according to that.

175
00:17:25,009 --> 00:17:27,451
So it had become a personal truth for him.

176
00:17:28,913 --> 00:17:39,709
Because of his ability to see things, he was able also to see beings passing from one realm to the other according to the same law.

177
00:17:40,130 --> 00:17:44,035
So what had been a personal law then became a cosmic law for him.

178
00:17:44,055 --> 00:17:45,436
That according to your

179
00:17:45,703 --> 00:17:48,268
ethical actions, you'll reap the results.

180
00:17:50,692 --> 00:17:51,353
Good or bad, yeah?

181
00:17:53,194 --> 00:18:00,707
And the third thing, so these two were just deep insights into the way things were, but they didn't liberate him.

182
00:18:00,866 --> 00:18:10,682
The liberation came with the collapse of ignorance and the answer to the question of who am I?

183
00:18:11,462 --> 00:18:12,505
Who am I?

184
00:18:13,935 --> 00:18:24,488
And that led to this, what people find a very confusing sort of doctrine of anatta, not self.

185
00:18:24,528 --> 00:18:32,436
The first thing is, it's not a philosophical statement, it's not a metaphysical statement, it's a technique to investigate ourselves.

186
00:18:32,457 --> 00:18:41,866
So, when we're sitting, or anywhere, every time you experience something, and you recognize there's a split between

187
00:18:42,049 --> 00:18:54,000
that which is experiencing and the experience, there's a split in your consciousness, then every time that happens, whatever you're experiencing can't be you, can't be, there's a break.

188
00:18:54,740 --> 00:18:56,821
And this goes back and back.

189
00:18:56,882 --> 00:18:59,365
It goes back from the body in its sensations.

190
00:18:59,605 --> 00:19:02,568
It goes, you step back from the heart with its emotions.

191
00:19:02,990 --> 00:19:05,132
And you step back from the mind with its thoughts.

192
00:19:06,012 --> 00:19:15,084
And the final one is this feeling of presence, the feeling of being that we might have occasionally.

193
00:19:15,443 --> 00:19:17,185
A sort of self-awareness.

194
00:19:17,205 --> 00:19:20,730
So even that, you see, if you're aware of a self, you can't be that either, can you?

195
00:19:20,710 --> 00:19:47,882
that's also an object so this movement backwards off what you're actually experiencing is the process of liberation so the basic existential delusion lies within that who am I so as a child I don't think we made any distinction between me and my body

196
00:19:48,722 --> 00:20:16,991
later on we can begin to use a certain language like I am feeling unwell where you think your illness but you know I have a headache so we already have a sort of a dualistic relationship to what we experience and that process of identity and possession is at the core of all our suffering and the reason is that

197
00:20:18,372 --> 00:20:24,662
Once you have identified something, I am, I am this, I am that, what is your search?

198
00:20:24,702 --> 00:20:25,723
Your search is for happiness.

199
00:20:27,287 --> 00:20:30,311
So you've got to search it within what you think you are.

200
00:20:30,893 --> 00:20:33,718
So if you think you're a human being, you've got to make it right here and now.

201
00:20:34,920 --> 00:20:43,012
If you think it's to do with pleasure, then you've got to manipulate the world to make sure it's giving you as much pleasure as you can, because only then do you feel happy.

202
00:20:43,803 --> 00:20:53,296
If you think it's relationship then you're constantly dependent upon somebody else for your personal happiness.

203
00:20:53,336 --> 00:20:58,943
You form an attachment and at worst an identity with what you're experiencing.

204
00:21:00,326 --> 00:21:06,334
And it's only when you begin to realize that there's an aftermath to these experiences

205
00:21:06,549 --> 00:21:11,798
that you begin to have the same inklings that the Buddha had, that maybe there's something else, maybe I've got something wrong here.

206
00:21:12,579 --> 00:21:17,146
Because in Buddhist understanding, nobody or nothing can cause you psychological pain.

207
00:21:17,607 --> 00:21:18,670
It's all self-inflicted.

208
00:21:20,393 --> 00:21:23,176
Pain in the body is a given.

209
00:21:23,196 --> 00:21:24,398
You can't do much about that.

210
00:21:24,440 --> 00:21:26,282
The body has its own life form.

211
00:21:26,303 --> 00:21:27,324
But suffering is optional.

212
00:21:28,125 --> 00:21:29,587
And we've opted to suffer.

213
00:21:30,631 --> 00:21:31,731
mainly because of delusion.

214
00:21:32,593 --> 00:21:39,098
So, the process of liberation is that process of detachment.

215
00:21:39,759 --> 00:21:40,500
Detachment.

216
00:21:41,500 --> 00:21:43,863
And that's what the meditation is about, the one I've just taught you.

217
00:21:44,482 --> 00:21:50,689
It's about beginning to realize that I'm not this, I don't own this, I'm not that, I don't own that.

218
00:21:51,088 --> 00:21:51,390
You see?

219
00:21:52,289 --> 00:21:58,596
Now, people think, therefore, if you continue this process, you just end up being nothing, just a blob.

220
00:21:59,807 --> 00:22:02,492
Because you're not this, not that.

221
00:22:02,512 --> 00:22:05,857
Well, you do, you just sit under a tree looking enlightened.

222
00:22:07,520 --> 00:22:18,259
But what happens is, of course, is that in undermining the wrong relationship to the world, we discover a proper relationship.

223
00:22:18,278 --> 00:22:23,587
And what we discover is that everything we thought we were letting go on is given back to us.

224
00:22:23,820 --> 00:22:38,758
So once the Buddha was enlightened, all the intellect that he had developed through his discussions and arguments at home and whatnot, came to the service of expressing the Dhamma.

225
00:22:40,020 --> 00:22:48,512
all the earlier attachments which he would have considered as love, as compassion, was cleansed of that attachment.

226
00:22:48,932 --> 00:22:58,906
But there was immediately after his realizing what he'd understood, there was an immediate desire to express this for others out of compassion.

227
00:22:59,688 --> 00:23:03,153
Immediate connection with other beings to bring them out of suffering.

228
00:23:05,655 --> 00:23:09,842
And as soon as he did that, there was a bit of a shake because he didn't think anybody could understand it.

229
00:23:10,446 --> 00:23:20,141
and the great god Sahampati came down and asked him to teach because some people had only a little dust in their eyes.

230
00:23:21,143 --> 00:23:25,930
So then, having determined to teach, off he goes, he walks, and that's his action.

231
00:23:26,810 --> 00:23:33,259
So within that enlightenment, these three questions become answered.

232
00:23:33,279 --> 00:23:37,787
What he is in terms of his ultimate state,

233
00:23:37,867 --> 00:23:40,570
what his relationship is to the world and what he has to do.

234
00:23:42,752 --> 00:23:46,758
And I started off by saying that his life was archetypal.

235
00:23:47,337 --> 00:23:49,681
So we also have to go through that process.

236
00:23:51,423 --> 00:23:56,989
And I think you'll find it right across the board of the spiritual life.

237
00:23:57,630 --> 00:24:06,019
No matter what spiritual form it takes, Christianity, Islam and whatnot, if you look at the mystics, they're all doing the same thing.

238
00:24:08,007 --> 00:24:08,647
one way or the other.

239
00:24:11,211 --> 00:24:13,773
There has to be a leaving of the world to re-find it.

240
00:24:17,917 --> 00:24:18,739
So don't look so glum.

241
00:24:21,923 --> 00:24:30,573
In the end, in the end you're happy.

242
00:24:30,593 --> 00:24:32,394
He was happy and he died very peacefully.

243
00:24:33,538 --> 00:24:34,400
Died on his side.

244
00:24:34,740 --> 00:24:37,403
He said, right before he died, he said, any more questions?

245
00:24:37,423 --> 00:24:37,984
Can you imagine?

246
00:24:38,005 --> 00:24:40,208
Any more questions?

247
00:24:41,769 --> 00:24:42,431
What will be ours?

248
00:24:42,990 --> 00:24:43,531
Why me?

249
00:24:47,136 --> 00:24:50,922
And then he was able, and then he gave his last piece of advice.

250
00:24:50,942 --> 00:24:52,944
All compounded things arise and pass away.

251
00:24:52,984 --> 00:24:54,747
Work diligently for your liberation.

252
00:24:58,151 --> 00:24:58,652
Just like that.

253
00:25:04,942 --> 00:25:06,499
So that's the end of my little homily.

